T1  - Managerial and Organizational Cognition: Theory, Methods and Research
AU  - Stimpert, J. L.
Y1  - 1999/04/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1999.1893943
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1999.1893943
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 360
EP  - 362
VL  - 24
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The book ?Managerial and Organizational Cognition: Theory, Methods and Research,? edited by Colin Eden and J. C. Spender, examines the nature of organizational knowledge, focusing specifically on the ?level-of-analysis? problem?that is, what we mean by the concepts of organizational cognition and organizational learning, given that only individuals have brains and think. The book draws on an eclectic set of ideas to examine the role of individual agency in managing the interaction between business organizations and their environments. The edited volume also addresses questions of both levels of analysis and individual agency by suggesting how organizational change can be engineered through the management of cognitive change among individual managers.
AB  - The book ?Managerial and Organizational Cognition: Theory, Methods and Research,? edited by Colin Eden and J. C. Spender, examines the nature of organizational knowledge, focusing specifically on the ?level-of-analysis? problem?that is, what we mean by the concepts of organizational cognition and organizational learning, given that only individuals have brains and think. The book draws on an eclectic set of ideas to examine the role of individual agency in managing the interaction between business organizations and their environments. The edited volume also addresses questions of both levels of analysis and individual agency by suggesting how organizational change can be engineered through the management of cognitive change among individual managers.
